	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Arcade-perfect &quot;Pac-Man&quot; version?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">DRW wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Has anyone tried those standalone plug &amp; play versions?<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.amazon.com/dp/B008AG4TZI">http://www.amazon.com/dp/B008AG4TZI</a><!-- m --></div><br /><br />I haven't played with that one, but I've seen a few others.<br /><br />The original Jakks Pacific Pac-Man unit is not particularly accurate. None of the games on it are. I am not sure what hardware it is based on, but it has a TERRIBLE composite encoder and can only make 50% duty square waves. The games on here are mediocre re-writes. Dig-Dug does not play correctly at all and all semblance to the original is superficial. I have not verified proper ghost behavior in pac-man.<br /><br />The Jakks Pacific Ms. Pac-Man one, however, is extremely accurate, and seems to have custom hardware made for it with very well written ports. I say ports because a lot of the weird edge-case behaviors and bugs are present in the games. I notice this most with Mappy. There is one bug, by the way, where after opening a flashing door in Mappy one of the music channels cuts out (the second voice of the main melody) until the level ends.<br /><br />I found a pretty neato debug mode / sound test for the original Plug and Play Ms. Pac-Man unit by Jakks Pacific that showed me that it contained all the sounds to Pac-Man, even though the game was not on there! If I get my hands on one I'll try to document this.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


